body:
It's not a bug of JDT.
The correct fix is to create a CtMultiTypeReference in spoon.

A workaround will be to create a CtTypeRefence of a Object.
You can do it by adding the following snippet at this position (all tests pass) https://github.com/INRIA/spoon/blob/master/src/main/java/spoon/support/compiler/jdt/ReferenceBuilder.java#L678

``` java
       else if (binding instanceof PolyTypeBinding) {
            ref = this.jdtTreeBuilder.getFactory().Core().createTypeReference();
            ref.setImplicit(isImplicit || !this.jdtTreeBuilder.getContextBuilder().isLambdaParameterImplicitlyTyped);
            ref.setDeclaringType(this.jdtTreeBuilder.getFactory().Type().objectType());
            ref.setSimpleName(Object.class.getCanonicalName());
        }
```
